<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1959,2021]" lastBlockId="7.[151,1437,151,1977]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="508" pageId="6" pageNumber="507">
The name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schoepff" authorityYear="1792" box="[275,455,1959,1984]" class="Reptilia" family="Testudinidae" genus="Testudo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Testudines" pageId="6" pageNumber="507" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="galeata">
<emphasis box="[275,455,1959,1984]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="507">Testudo galeata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was erected by 
<bibRefCitation author="Schoepff, I. D." box="[647,828,1959,1984]" pageId="6" pageNumber="507" refId="ref13074" refString="Schoepff, I. D. (1792) Historia Testudinum iconibus illustrata. Ioannes Iacobus Palm, Erlangen, XII + 136 pp., 31 plates. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 5109" type="book" year="1792">Schoepff (1792</bibRefCitation>
: p. 12) in his famous “ 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="507">Historia Testudinum iconibus illustrata</emphasis>
”. For a long time 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schoepff" authorityYear="1792" box="[466,644,1996,2021]" class="Reptilia" family="Testudinidae" genus="Testudo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Testudines" pageId="6" pageNumber="507" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="galeata">
<emphasis box="[466,644,1996,2021]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="507">Testudo galeata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was used for helmeted terrapins, until 
<bibRefCitation author="Mertens, R." box="[1089,1264,1996,2021]" pageId="6" pageNumber="507" pagination="139 - 142" refId="ref12650" refString="Mertens, R. (1937) Bemerkungen uber die Rassen von Pelomedusa subrufa (La Cepede). Zoologischer Anzeiger, 117, 139 - 142." type="journal article" year="1937">Mertens (1937)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Loveridge, A." lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="508" pageId="6" pageNumber="507" pagination="467 - 524" refId="ref12616" refString="Loveridge, A. (1941) Revision of the African terrapin [sic] of the family Pelomedusidae. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology, 88, 467 - 524." type="journal article" year="1941">Loveridge (1941)</bibRefCitation>
pointed out that the older name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bonnaterre" authorityYear="1789" box="[613,796,151,176]" class="Reptilia" family="Testudinidae" genus="Testudo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Testudines" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="subrufa">
<emphasis box="[613,796,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Testudo subrufa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should be applied. Schoepff’s original description was based on detailed unpublished notes received from two Swedish naturalists. Originally, 
<bibRefCitation author="Schoepff, I. D." box="[1128,1304,188,213]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" refId="ref13074" refString="Schoepff, I. D. (1792) Historia Testudinum iconibus illustrata. Ioannes Iacobus Palm, Erlangen, XII + 136 pp., 31 plates. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 5109" type="book" year="1792">Schoepff (1792</bibRefCitation>
: pp. 12–16) intended to assemble information about another terrapin species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Linnaeus, 1758" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[899,1257,223,248]" class="Reptilia" family="Testudinidae" genus="Testudo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Testudines" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scabra">
<emphasis box="[899,1071,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Testudo scabra</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Linnaeus, C." box="[1080,1257,223,248]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" pagination="1" refId="ref12541" refString="Linnaeus, C. (1758) Systema naturae per regna tria naturae, secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis. Tomus I. Regnum animale. Editio decima, reformata. Laurentius Salvius, Stockholm, (3) + 823 + (1) pp. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 542" type="journal article" year="1758">Linnaeus, 1758</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, a taxon whose identity puzzled scientists for about 250 years (
<bibRefCitation author="Rhodin, A. G. J. &amp; Carr, J. L." box="[679,916,260,285]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" pagination="1 - 18" refId="ref12821" refString="Rhodin, A. G. J. &amp; Carr, J. L. (2009) A quarter millenium of uses and misuses of the turtle name Testudo scabra: identification of the type specimens of T. scabra Linnaeus 1758 (= Rhinoclemmys punctularia) and T. scripta Thunberg in Schoepff 1792 (= Trachemys scripta scripta). Zootaxa, 2226, 1 - 18." type="journal article" year="2009">Rhodin &amp; Carr 2009</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1977]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">
Schoepff received from Anders Jahan Retzius (1742–1821) of Lund a detailed description and drawings of a “ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[163,332,332,357]" class="Reptilia" family="Testudinidae" genus="Testudo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Testudines" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scabra">
<emphasis box="[163,332,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Testudo scabra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” from “ 
<collectingCountry box="[424,484,332,357]" name="India" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">India</collectingCountry>
orientalis” [East 
<collectingCountry box="[679,742,332,357]" name="India" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">India</collectingCountry>
], which Retzius had kept alive for two years. 
<bibRefCitation author="Schoepff, I. D." box="[1254,1436,332,357]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" refId="ref13074" refString="Schoepff, I. D. (1792) Historia Testudinum iconibus illustrata. Ioannes Iacobus Palm, Erlangen, XII + 136 pp., 31 plates. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 5109" type="book" year="1792">Schoepff (1792)</bibRefCitation>
published Retzius’ description (pp. 13–14) and a coloured etching of the terrapin as figure 
<quantity box="[1197,1242,367,392]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.54" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" unit="in" value="1.0">1 in</quantity>
plate III. Shown under the name “ 
<taxonomicName authority="Retz." authorityName="Retz." box="[341,543,404,429]" class="Reptilia" family="Testudinidae" genus="Testudo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Testudines" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scabra">
<emphasis box="[341,474,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Test. scabra</emphasis>
Retz.
</taxonomicName>
”, it is clearly a juvenile 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bonnaterre" baseAuthorityYear="1789" box="[810,1039,404,429]" class="Reptilia" family="Pelomedusidae" genus="Pelomedusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Testudines" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="subrufa">
<emphasis box="[810,1039,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Pelomedusa subrufa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1054,1121,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1597,1619]" captionTargetBox="[224,1354,222,1560]" captionTargetId="figure-260@8.[209,1384,195,1578]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Top, left: Folio from Schoepff’s legacy (Museum für Naturkunde zu Berlin, Historische Bild- und Schriftgutsammlungen, SI, Nachl. Schoepff II) consisting of the drawings provided by Retzius and an imprint of the resultant etching. Retzius’ hand-written German text reads:" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4915070" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4915070/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
, top), and “Prof. D. Swartz” (probably to be identified with Olof Peter Swartz, 1760–1818) of Stockholm wrote to Schoepff that a very similar specimen in spirit is present in the Cabinet of the Royal Academy of Sciences at Stockholm. 
<bibRefCitation author="Schoepff, I. D." box="[1185,1361,476,501]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" refId="ref13074" refString="Schoepff, I. D. (1792) Historia Testudinum iconibus illustrata. Ioannes Iacobus Palm, Erlangen, XII + 136 pp., 31 plates. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 5109" type="book" year="1792">Schoepff (1792</bibRefCitation>
: p. 16) concluded that these two terrapins could represent a new species, for which he proposed the name 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schoepff" authorityYear="1792" box="[1252,1429,511,536]" class="Reptilia" family="Testudinidae" genus="Testudo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Testudines" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="galeata">
<emphasis box="[1252,1429,511,536]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Testudo galeata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The eponymous character (
<taxonomicName authority=", Latin" authorityName="Latin" box="[456,613,548,573]" class="Reptilia" family="Testudinidae" genus="Testudo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Testudines" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="galeata">
<emphasis box="[456,540,548,573]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">galeata</emphasis>
, Latin
</taxonomicName>
= helmeted) of this putative new species is its helmet-like head scalation. The two terrapins from Lund and Stockholm have to be regarded as 
<typeStatus box="[915,1013,584,608]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">syntypes</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName box="[1051,1228,583,608]" class="Reptilia" family="Testudinidae" genus="Testudo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Testudines" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="galeata">
<emphasis box="[1051,1228,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Testudo galeata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1977]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">
In the collection of the Biological Museum of Lund University there is still extant a single alcohol-preserved 
<taxonomicName box="[151,288,655,680]" class="Reptilia" family="Pelomedusidae" genus="Pelomedusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Testudines" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,288,655,680]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Pelomedusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimen, bearing the catalogue number ZMUL 6481 (
<figureCitation box="[906,974,655,680]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1597,1619]" captionTargetBox="[224,1354,222,1560]" captionTargetId="figure-260@8.[209,1384,195,1578]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Top, left: Folio from Schoepff’s legacy (Museum für Naturkunde zu Berlin, Historische Bild- und Schriftgutsammlungen, SI, Nachl. Schoepff II) consisting of the drawings provided by Retzius and an imprint of the resultant etching. Retzius’ hand-written German text reads:" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4915070" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4915070/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
, bottom). Retzius donated this terrapin as “ 
<taxonomicName box="[163,333,692,717]" class="Reptilia" family="Testudinidae" genus="Testudo" kingdom="Animalia" order="Testudines" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="scabra">
<emphasis box="[163,333,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Testudo scabra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” in 1811 to the Lund Museum, together with a large collection of other specimens (L. Lundqvist, pers. comm.). We conclude that ZMUL 6481, which originates evidently from Retzius, has to be identified with the 
<typeStatus box="[151,238,764,788]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">syntype</typeStatus>
described in detail in 
<bibRefCitation author="Schoepff, I. D." box="[486,663,764,789]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" refId="ref13074" refString="Schoepff, I. D. (1792) Historia Testudinum iconibus illustrata. Ioannes Iacobus Palm, Erlangen, XII + 136 pp., 31 plates. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 5109" type="book" year="1792">Schoepff (1792</bibRefCitation>
: pp. 13–14). The size of ZMUL 6481 (straight carapacial length 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.84" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" unit="cm" value="5.84">5.84 cm</quantity>
, width 
<quantity box="[276,372,799,824]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.97" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" unit="cm" value="4.97">4.97 cm</quantity>
) approximately matches the measurements given in 
<bibRefCitation author="Schoepff, I. D." box="[983,1163,799,824]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" refId="ref13074" refString="Schoepff, I. D. (1792) Historia Testudinum iconibus illustrata. Ioannes Iacobus Palm, Erlangen, XII + 136 pp., 31 plates. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 5109" type="book" year="1792">Schoepff (1792</bibRefCitation>
: p. 13) with 2 ½ and 2 Prussian inches (1 Prussian inch = 
<quantity box="[551,661,836,861]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.615" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" unit="cm" value="2.615">2.615 cm</quantity>
), especially when it is considered that Retzius could have measured over the curve of the carapace. However, the shell shape of ZMUL 6481 is a bit too oval compared to Schoepff’s figure (
<figureCitation box="[237,309,908,933]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1597,1619]" captionTargetBox="[224,1354,222,1560]" captionTargetId="figure-260@8.[209,1384,195,1578]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Top, left: Folio from Schoepff’s legacy (Museum für Naturkunde zu Berlin, Historische Bild- und Schriftgutsammlungen, SI, Nachl. Schoepff II) consisting of the drawings provided by Retzius and an imprint of the resultant etching. Retzius’ hand-written German text reads:" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4915070" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4915070/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
, top). Retzius’ two original drawings of the terrapin and part of his letter have survived among Schoepff’s legacy, and are now kept in the Museum für Naturkunde, 
<collectingRegion box="[923,993,943,968]" country="Germany" name="Berlin" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Berlin</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation box="[1008,1077,943,968]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1597,1619]" captionTargetBox="[224,1354,222,1560]" captionTargetId="figure-260@8.[209,1384,195,1578]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Top, left: Folio from Schoepff’s legacy (Museum für Naturkunde zu Berlin, Historische Bild- und Schriftgutsammlungen, SI, Nachl. Schoepff II) consisting of the drawings provided by Retzius and an imprint of the resultant etching. Retzius’ hand-written German text reads:" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4915070" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4915070/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
, top). The original drawings are very rough, but they illustrate a shell shape that agrees better with ZMUL 6481 than with 
<bibRefCitation author="Schoepff, I. D." box="[1229,1436,980,1005]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" refId="ref13074" refString="Schoepff, I. D. (1792) Historia Testudinum iconibus illustrata. Ioannes Iacobus Palm, Erlangen, XII + 136 pp., 31 plates. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 5109" type="book" year="1792">Schoepff’s (1792)</bibRefCitation>
published figure. In comparison it appears that Schoepff’s figure is somewhat idealized. The coloration of the 
<typeStatus box="[151,238,1052,1076]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508">syntype</typeStatus>
is much faded due to the age of the specimen and allows no direct comparison with the description in 
<bibRefCitation author="Schoepff, I. D." box="[151,336,1087,1112]" pageId="7" pageNumber="508" refId="ref13074" refString="Schoepff, I. D. (1792) Historia Testudinum iconibus illustrata. Ioannes Iacobus Palm, Erlangen, XII + 136 pp., 31 plates. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 5109" type="book" year="1792">Schoepff (1792)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
